You might want to look into the [Dual Simplex Method][1] (or [Duality Theory][2]). If the standard form of the primal problem is:
    
    Maximize = 13*X1 + 23*X2;

with constraints:

    5*X1	+	15*X2	&lt;= 480;
    4*X1 	+ 	4*X2 	&lt;= 160;
    35*X1   + 	20*X2   &lt;= 1190;
    X1 &gt;= 0;
    X2 &gt;= 0;

Then the **dual problem** is:

    Minimize = 480*Y1 + 160*Y2 + 1190*Y3;

with constraints:

    5*Y1	+	4*Y2	+	35*Y3	&gt;= 13;
    15*Y1 + 	4*Y2	+	20*Y3	&gt;= 23;
    Y1 &gt;= 0;
    Y2 &gt;= 0;
    Y3 &gt;= 0;

I tested both of these problems in [LINGO][3] and get the same answer for both (Z = 800, X1 = 12, X2 = 28 -- Y1 = 1, Y2 = 2, Y3 = 0).


  [1]: http://homepages.rpi.edu/~mitchj/handouts/dualsimplex/
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming#Duality
  [3]: http://www.lindo.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=2&amp;Itemid=10

